LAGOS – Managing Director, Shell Petroleum Development Company and Country Chair, Shell Companies in Nigeria, Mr. Osagie Okunbor, is excited that government partners and stakeholders recognised Shell’s significant contributions to the revenue of Nigeria. He said on account of this, the government is able to grow the economy and bring about developments to every part of the country. He spoke at a recent award ceremony in Abuja, as part of the second annual National Tax Dialogue, Shell companies in Nigeria. His company was named Shell as a “leading tax compliant organisation in Nigeria for 2021.”It also won the award for ‘remarkable performance in the remittance of various taxes’ in the same year Okunbor said: “Nigeria is an important heartland for Shell, and will remain so. We will continue to invest in the country to help meet its energy needs, with a focus on growing our deep-water and gas positions.” Okunbor, who was represented at the event by a director of the SPDC and General Manager Business Government Relationship, Mr. Bashir Bello, said Shell companies would remain committed to expanding their gas portfolio for domestic and export market while also increasing access to energy for Nigerians.” The Shell Petroleum Development Company of Nigeria Limited (SPDC), Shell Nigeria Exploration and Production Company Limited (SNEPCo) and Shell Nigeria Gas paid a combined $6 billion in direct taxes between 2015 and 2020 to the government. Mr. Muhammad Mamman Nami , the Executive Chairman of the FIRS, while speaking, disclosed that Shell Petroleum Development Company of Nigeria Limited (SPDC), Shell Nigeria Exploration and Production Company Limited (SNEPCo) and Shell Nigeria Gas paid a combined $6 billion in direct taxes between 2015 and 2020 to the government. POLL He noted that Shell companies demonstrated commitment to paying all government taxes hence the two awards.